      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''City Approves 'Carbon Tax' in Effort to Reduce Gas Emissions'' (news article, Nov. 18):</p>
        <p>While the idea may be too modest to change behavior significantly, Boulder, Colo., is on the right track: It would be possible to transfer most, maybe all, of the local tax burden to a carbon tax.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''City Approves 'Carbon Tax' in Effort to Reduce Gas Emissions'' (news article, Nov. 18):</p>
        <p>While the idea may be too modest to change behavior significantly, Boulder, Colo., is on the right track: It would be possible to transfer most, maybe all, of the local tax burden to a carbon tax.</p>
        <p>If done in a revenue-neutral way, and widened to include natural gas and a modest gas tax, this would offer a real incentive to change behavior.</p>
        <p>Since global warming is a much greater problem than the storage of nuclear waste, nuclear electricity should not be taxed.</p>
        <p>If other American cities follow Boulder's example, we may get a handle on global warming, and all by a simple tax change.</p>
        <p>Wilfred Candler  Annapolis, Md., Nov. 18, 2006</p>
      </block>
